&gt; In my opinion, you should reverse your test.  So, instead of failing
&gt; because the library has bad code, your test now fails if the library has
&gt; *good* code.  Then, you should have another test which tests *your* code
&gt; and makes sure that you prevent the bug from happening.

The problem I have is that now that all my tests pass with a buggy code,
how can I trust my tests?  What will remind me that my code is broken if
my failing tests pass?

If I&#39;m the only one on the project, I can keep track of the open issues
(like upgrading a library) but things get complicated as soon as you
have some decentralized organization (OSS e.g.)

I think it&#39;s important that you have a red flag somewhere, and possibly
automatic (not a todo list that you may or may not keep up-to-date).
For JUnit-addons, I wrote a validator that checks for tests that are not
starting with &quot;test&quot; and gives a notice.  I think that I will run this
automatically in my build and comment-out my test (like &quot;public void
failing-test&quot;): all my tests now pass but I have an automatic reminder
that they are in fact broken.  The rule will be: all the defined tests
must pass and no test must be commented-out.

-Vladimir

